Hi [First Name],

How is your school teaching students to navigate AI?
If you=E2=80=99re not sure where to start (or if computing education hasn=E2=
=80=99t been a priority yet) you=E2=80=99re not alone. Research shows that tw=
o-thirds of countries still lack comprehensive computing curricula, and AI li=
teracy is rarely integrated at all grade levels.[1]
But here=E2=80=99s what=E2=80=99s changed: By 2030, 85% of jobs will require =
some level of AI fluency.[2] The question isn=E2=80=99t whether schools need =
to teach computing and AI. It=E2=80=99s how to do it well across all grades, =
not just high school.
Here=E2=80=99s the problem most schools face: They cobble together free tools=
. Scratch for elementary, Code.org for middle school, maybe some Python tutor=
ials in high school. But these fragmented approaches lack progression, overwh=
elm teachers, and fail to prepare students for the AI-driven careers they=E2=
=80=99ll enter.
What if there was a better way?
Level Up Through Digital Discoveries is the only K-12 ICT curriculum that int=
egrates AI literacy from Grade 1 through Grade 12. It=E2=80=99s built on a pr=
ogressive =E2=80=9Cspiral learning=E2=80=9D model that ensures students don=
=E2=80=99t just learn to code, but learn to think computationally in an AI-po=
wered world.
Here=E2=80=99s what makes it different:
=E2=9C=93 Complete K-12 continuity =E2=80=93 Not a patchwork. One seamless cu=
rriculum from digital citizenship in kindergarten to machine learning in Grad=
e 12.
=E2=9C=93 AI integration at every grade =E2=80=93 Grade 1 students explore AI=
 basics through Scratch. Grade 7 students dive into generative AI and prompt =
engineering. Grade 12 students build predictive models and study natural lang=
uage processing.
=E2=9C=93 Standards-aligned globally =E2=80=93 Independently reviewed to meet=
 ISTE, CSTA, and UN SDG 4 frameworks. Prepares students for Cambridge IGCSE, =
IB, and AP pathways.
=E2=9C=93 Teacher support you can rely on =E2=80=93 Ready-to-teach lesson pla=
ns, pacing guides, and comprehensive teacher editions. No CS degree required.
=E2=9C=93 Bilingual classroom support =E2=80=93 Designed to support diverse l=
anguage backgrounds and promote equity in learning. Critical for internationa=
l schools with multilingual students.
=E2=9C=93 Flexible delivery =E2=80=93 Works in traditional, hybrid, or remote=
 settings. Print materials available now, with adaptive digital platform laun=
ching later this year.
I=E2=80=99d like to show you how Level Up can bring comprehensive computing e=
ducation to your school.
Here are three ways to learn more:
Explore the Full Program =E2=86=92
Download the Program Brochure (PDF) =E2=86=92
See How AI is Integrated Across All Grades (PDF) =E2=86=92
